[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "The Idea"]
[Result "*"]

{ There are videos circulating on YouTube from well-known streamers explaining how to trap an opponent in one specific sideline of a certain opening. It often turned out that hundreds, sometimes thousands of players commit a blunder or fall into a trap in a certain position. I also noticed that many players fail to punish a blunder in the opening.  With this series I want to change that: I provide a comprehensive overview of the most common blunders in the opening stage of the game. Furthermore, I will show you how to set opening traps without making an inferior move, and how to punish mistakes from your opponent.  This series is packed with inspiration for every player, from beginner to advanced  (2000 FIDE)  , but also for coaches of players of the same target group. I'm convinced that this series will help you turn your opponent's opening mistakes into quick wins in many cases. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "The Exercises"]
[Result "*"]

{ If you're looking at the exercises for the first time, I recommend viewing the full variation, from move 1, including all annotations.  All exercises are annotated to the maximum, and this should suffice for the vast majority of exercises. In a rare case, the end of the exercise concerns a very complex position that you should analyze more deeply with an engine.  The annotation is visually explained using arrows on the board: Blue arrows show candidates for the next move/moves, green arrows are used for defensive moves  (defending a piece, creating an escape square,…)  , indicating an open file/diagonal, and also for pins and checks, red arrows are used to indicate blunders and the punishment of blunders in sidelines.  If you do the exercises in study and review mode, you will see that you don't start from move 1. Only if the move to be made is clearly better than other moves, I have designated it as a key move.  The quality of all exercises was checked with the Stockfish 13 engine, although I also kept in mind which moves were made in practice, especially in case the engine offered several good moves  (including the most common move order)  , and the winrates that accompanied it.  The variations are grouped in chapters by opening. Within a chapter, the variations are first grouped by color. The order of the variations with the same color is from 'simple'  (sidelines)  to 'complex'  (main lines)  . This can best be explained by means of an example: In the Ruy López, 3... d6 is a sideline while 3... a6 is the main line. For that reason, variations with 3... d6 are discussed before the variations with 3... a6. After 3... a6 there are two main possibilities: 4. Bxc6 and 4. Ba4. The first is less common than the second according to the statistics that were used for this series, and for that reason variations with 4. Bxc6 are discussed before variations with 4. Ba4, and so on. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "How the Selection of Exercises was made"]
[Result "*"]

{ On lichess.org, all positions that meet the following conditions were searched:  - Lichess database with average rating: 1600, 1800, 2000, 2200 and 2500;  - Duration: Only Rapid and Classical, because with Bullet and Blitz there are too many obvious mistakes, like e.g. blundering a piece in 1 move;  - Positions that start with a blunder or mistake that has been played at least 200 times  (although there are a few exceptions to this in this series)  ;  - White OR Black won more than 70% of the games from that position.  This resulted in a list of more than 2,000 variations. These variations were then manually assessed 1 by 1. Only the variations that met all of the following conditions were retained:  - The exercise has to be instructive and not too similar to other variations;  - The engine analysis confirms a major advantage for the color with the high winrate: A number with a plus sign means an advantage for White, a number with a minus sign means an advantage for Black;  - You don't learn a lot from exercises where the blunders pile up on both sides. The selection of exercises that made it through this series contains a maximum of 1 dubious move for the winning side. Obviously, that dubious move will not be one of the key moves you have to study, but only the  (good)  moves that follow. There is no limit to the losing side's blunders or mistakes, as long as they are played frequently. }
