[White "2. Italian Game, Two Knights Defense"]
[Black "Modern Bishop's Opening (3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Italian Game } 3... Nf6 { Two Knights Defense } 4.
d3 { Modern Bishop's Opening, Defending  e4  . } 4... h6 { Preventing Ng5. } 5.
c3
{ Preparing d4 in some variations while preventing the Knight on  c6  to occupy  b4  or  d4  . }
5... d5 { A poor move: trying to take control over the center. } 6. exd5
{ Trading a pair of pawns, opening up the e-file. } 6... Nxd5 7. Qb3
{ Another benefit of the move c3 earlier in the game! The Knight on  d5  now is attacked twice. }
7... Be6
{ Developing the Bishop while protecting the Knight. But overlooking White's next move...   7...Na5  would have limited the damage for Black, although it also loses a pawn in view of  8.Qa4+  Nc6  9.Nxe5  . }
8. Qxb7 { Capturing an important Black queenside pawn. } 8... Na5
{ Black's last attempt to endanger White, forking Queen and Bishop. } 9. Bb5+
{ The easiest and most natural reply.   Black has to play the ugly  9...Ke7  here to avoid losing even more material @@StartBracket@@+2.0@@EndBracket@@.   9...Bd7  loses to  10.Bxd7+  Qxd7  11.Qxa8+  @@StartBracket@@+9.0@@EndBracket@@. }
