1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Italian Game } 3... Nf6 { Two Knights Defense } 4.
d4 { Open Variation, An agressive move. } 4... Nxe4
{ A mistake, played thousands of times!   A better continuation for Black is  4...exd4  5.e5  d5  6.Bb5  Ne4  7.Nxd4  Bd7  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.O-O  Bc5  @@StartBracket@@+0.0@@EndBracket@@. }
5. dxe5 { The only move for White to keep an edge. } 5... Bc5
{ The most played move in this position actually is a blunder... } 6. Qd5
{ Threatening checkmate on  f7  while attacking Black's pieces in the center of the board. }
6... Bxf2+ { A desperate try... } 7. Ke2
{ The best square for the King according to the engine. But it doesn't really matter, White is way ahead. }
7... O-O { Preventing a checkmate. } 8. Qxe4
{ Capturing a free Knight. White is a piece and a pawn up, has the most active pieces and is controlling the center @@StartBracket@@+5.0@@EndBracket@@.  Another common variation with similar tactics can be reached via the Giuoco Piano, Center Attack:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Bc5  (Giuoco Piuano)  4.c3  Nf6  5.d4  (Center Attack)  5...Bb6  6.dxe5  Nxe4  7.Qd5  Bxf2+  .  The only difference in the end is the pawn on  c3  for White. Black lost a tempo by playing Bb6 before capturing on  f2  . }
