1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Italian Game } 3... Nf6 { Two Knights Defense } 4.
Ng5 { Knight Attack } 4... d5 { Normal Variation } 5. exd5 Na5
{ Polerio Defense } 6. Bb5+
{ Bishop Check Line, by far the most played move in this position. } 6... Bd7
{ Blocking the check with the light-squared Bishop, challenging White's Bishop. }
7. Qe2
{ The best move to keep a slight advantage: Defending the Bishop on  b5  while attacking the pawn on  e5  . }
7... Nxd5
{ Grabbing White's center pawn while attacking the Knight on  g5  with a discovered attack. A poor move, played hundreds of times. }
8. Qxe5+ { This move solves all White's problems. } 8... Ne7
{ Saving the Knight, but overlooking White's next move.   8...Qe7  would have been better. White can't capture the Knight because it is pinned to the King. The game could continu with  9.Qxe7+  Kxe7  10.Bxd7  Kxd7  11.Nxf7  @@StartBracket@@+2.0@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Bxd7+ { A forced exchange of Bishops. } 9... Qxd7 10. Qxa5
{ Capturing a free Knight. White is a piece and a pawn up @@StartBracket@@+4.5@@EndBracket@@. }
