[Black "Two Knights Variation (2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Italian Game } 3... Nf6 { Two Knights Defense } 4.
O-O { A dubious move, played over 100,000 times!! } 4... Nxe4
{ Grabbing a center pawn. } 5. Re1 { Putting a Rook on the semi-open file. }
5... d5
{ A key move in this variation! Defending the Knight while attacking White's Bishop. }
6. Bb5 { The most played move at this point, pinning the Knight to the King. }
6... Bc5
{ Lining up the Bishop with White's King, attacking  f2  for a second time. }
7. d4
{ White's best move in the position: Giving back the pawn in order to disturb the coordination of Black's pieces.   7.Re2  has been tried, but isn't good in view of  7...Nxf2  8.Rxf2  Bxf2+  9.Kxf2  e4  @@StartBracket@@-3.0@@EndBracket@@. }
7... exd4
{ Again a key move, the only move to keep the advantage @@StartBracket@@-2.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Nxd4
{ This move has been played in the majority of the games. But it only makes things worse for White... }
8... O-O { A brilliant and calm reply! } 9. Bxc6
{ Black usually tries to simplify the position by trading pieces. } 9... Nxf2
{ You shouldn't care about material when you can hunt down the enemy King. This move is absolutely crushing @@StartBracket@@-5.0@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Kxf2 { What else... } 10... Qf6+
{ Forking King and Knight.   After  11.Kg1  Qxd4+  12.Qxd4  Bxd4+  13.Kh1  bxc6  , dust has settled. Black is up two pawns and has the Bishop pair, while White's queenside still is undeveloped @@StartBracket@@-5.0@@EndBracket@@. }
*

