[Black "Knight Attack, Ulvestad Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Italian Game } 3... Nf6 { Two Knights Defense } 4.
Ng5 { Knight Attack } 4... d5 { Normal Variation } 5. exd5 b5
{ Ulvestad Variation, an interesting sideline, especially in case White hasn't seen it before. }
6. Bxb5
{ White's best move in this position is  6.Bf1  . The game could continu with  6...Nxd5  7.Bxb5 }
6... Qxd5
{ This is the reason why 6. Bxb5 wasn't the best move: Black now attacks both the Bishop and the pawn on  g2  . }
7. Bxc6+ { Exchanging minor pieces. } 7... Qxc6 8. O-O Bb7
{ Threatening checkmate on  g2  . } 9. f3
{ A mistake.  9.Qf3  is the only good move in this position for White. Black can't play  9...Qxc2  in view of  10.Qxb7 }
9... h6
{ Chasing away White's only active piece to a bad square. Black is better according to the engine  (-3.0)  , despite being a pawn down. White's pieces are having a backrankfest, while Black's pieces are developed and eyeing the enemy King.   The game could continu with  10.Nh3  , followed by  10...g5  or  10...O-O-O }
*

