1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Italian Game } 3... Bc5 { Giuoco Piano Game } 4.
c3 { Main Line, Preparing a d4-push later in the game. } 4... d6
{ This move has been played almost 100,000 times on lower levels! But it's not a very good one... }
5. d4 { Challenging Black's center. } 5... exd4
{ Trading a pair of center pawns. } 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nc3
{ Blocking the check while self-pinning the Knight.   I'm not a fan of  7.Bd2  because it allows a trade of Bishops @@StartBracket@@+0.5@@EndBracket@@.   7.Kf1  could be an interesting alternative. The idea is to play  d5  next move, followed by  Qa4+  , forking King and Bishop on  b4  . }
7... Bg4
{ Pinning the other Knight to the Queen. It looks like White is under pressure, but that's not really the case! }
8. O-O
{ Stepping out of the pin by castling. The Knight on  c3  is now free to move. }
8... Qf6
{ Increasing the pressure on  f3  is a big mistake!   8...Nge7  isn't good either, since it allows  9.Bxf7+  Kxf7  10.Ng5+  Ke8  11.Qxg4  @@StartBracket@@+5.5@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Nd5
{ The Knight that was unpinned previous move steps forward, forking Queen, Bishop and the pawn on  c7  . }
9... Qd8 { The Queen has to retreat and defend  c7  . } 10. Nxb4
{ Trading minor pieces. } 10... Nxb4 11. Qb3
{ An excellent move, attacking  f7  while threatening to capture the Knight.   11.Qa4  is good too, in view of  11...Nc6  12.d5  a6!  13.dxc6  b5  14.Bxf7+  Kxf7  15.Qb3+  @@StartBracket@@+5.0@@EndBracket@@. }
11... Bxf3 { Initiating a trade of minor pieces. } 12. Bxf7+
{ Giving a check first by capturing a pawn. } 12... Kf8 13. Bxg8
{ Threatening checkmate on  f7  . } 13... Rxg8 14. Qxf3+
{ Keeping the pawns on the kingside intact @@StartBracket@@+6.5@@EndBracket@@. White is only a pawn up, but Black's King isn't safe. White should keep the Queens on the board and try to grab some extra pawns. }
