1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Italian Game } 3... Bc5 { Giuoco Piano Game } 4.
c3 { Main Line, Preparing a d4-push later in the game. } 4... Nf6
{ Attacking the pawn on  e4  , by far the most common reply by great players. }
5. d4 { Center Attack, The most common move. } 5... exd4
{ Trading a pair of center pawns.   In theItalian Game, Two Knights Variation, Open Variation, we already described what would happen after  5...Bb6  . White should continue with  6.dxe5  Nxe4?  7.Qd5  @@StartBracket@@+4.5@@EndBracket@@.   5...d6?  simply fails to  6.dxc5  @@StartBracket@@+5.0@@EndBracket@@. }
6. cxd4 { Traditional Line } 6... Bb4+ 7. Nc3
{ Greco Attack, A dubious move according to Stockfish 13. White choses to self-pin his Knight. }
7... Nxe4
{ Capturing a center pawn and attacking the Knight on  c3  with a second piece. }
8. O-O { King safety first! } 8... Nxc3
{ 8...Bxc3  would have been slightly better, as we saw in previous variations. }
9. bxc3
{ 9.Re1+  Be7  10.bxc3  is the alternative @@StartBracket@@+0.0@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Bxc3 { A very poor move that was played thousands of times. } 10. Ba3
{ A brilliant move, preventing Black from castling. White doesn't care about material at this point.   10.Qb3?!  isn't the best, in view of  10...d5!!  11.Bxd5  O-O!  If White now captures the Bishop, Black will do the same @@StartBracket@@+0.5@@EndBracket@@. }
10... d5
{ Black's only chance. In the previous variation, there wasn't a pawn on d7 anymore.   10...Bxa1  fails to  11.Re1+  Ne7  12.Bxe7  Qxe7  13.Qxa1  @@StartBracket@@+6.0@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Bb5 { Pinning the Knight to the King. } 11... Bxa1
{ Black is happy to grab even more material. } 12. Re1+
{ White is currently a Rook and 2 pawns down, but Black will have huge difficulties to defend this position. }
12... Be6 { Developing a piece while blocking the check. } 13. Qc2
{ Attacking the Knight on  c6  with a second piece. } 13... Qd7
{ Defending the Knight. } 14. Ne5
{ Forking Queen and Knight. Black is in trouble! } 14... Nxe5
{ An interesting solution to Black's problem. } 15. Bxd7+ Nxd7 16. Rxa1
{ White should be better in this highly unbalanced position @@StartBracket@@+3.0@@EndBracket@@. }
