1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Italian Game } 3... Bc5 { Giuoco Piano Game } 4.
c3 { Main Line, Preparing a d4-push later in the game. } 4... Nf6
{ Attacking the pawn on  e4  , by far the most common reply by great players. }
5. d4 { Center Attack, The most common move. } 5... exd4
{ Trading a pair of center pawns.   In theItalian Game, Two Knights Variation, Open Variation, we already described what would happen after  5...Bb6  . White should continue with  6.dxe5  Nxe4?  7.Qd5  @@StartBracket@@+4.5@@EndBracket@@.   5...d6?  simply fails to  6.dxc5  @@StartBracket@@+5.0@@EndBracket@@. }
6. cxd4 { Traditional Line } 6... Bb4+ 7. Nc3
{ Greco Attack, A dubious move according to Stockfish 13. White choses to self-pin his Knight. }
7... Nxe4
{ Capturing a center pawn and attacking the Knight on  c3  with a second piece. }
8. O-O { King safety first! } 8... Bxc3
{ The only move to keep a slight edge.   8...Nxc3  9.bxc3  Bxc3?  is bad in view of  10.Ba3  . Black's King is stuck in the middle of the board @@StartBracket@@+3.0@@EndBracket@@. }
9. d5 { An interesting idea, even at top level. } 9... Ne5
{ Attacking the Bishop.   Sometimes Black prefers  9...Bf6  , in view of  10.Re1  Ne7  11.Rxe4  d6  @@StartBracket@@-0.5@@EndBracket@@. }
10. bxc3 { 10.Qe2  is good too @@StartBracket@@-0.5@@EndBracket@@. } 10... Nxc4
11. Qd4 { Forking both Knights while attacking  g7  . } 11... Ncd6
{ Saving both Knights, although  11...O-O  appears to be better for Black in practice. Black is a piece and a pawn up, so it isn't a problem to give a piece back. }
12. Qxg7 { Capturing a pawn, attacking the Rook. } 12... Qf6
{ Defending the Rook with the Queen, offering a Queen trade. } 13. Qxf6
{ Exchanging Queens. } 13... Nxf6 14. Re1+
{ The only good move for White in this position! Remember, White still is a piece down at this point. }
14... Nfe4
{ An important move.   14...Kf8  fails to  15.Bh6+  Kg8  16.Re5  Nfe4  @@StartBracket@@+6.5@@EndBracket@@.   14...Kd8  is bad because of  15.Bg5  @@StartBracket@@+8.0@@EndBracket@@. }
15. Nd2 { Attacking the Knight in the center once more. } 15... f5
{ Defending the Knight. } 16. f3
{ Attacking the pinned Knight. Black will lose a piece, but e.g. after  16...O-O  17.fxe4  fxe4  18.Nxe4  Nxe4  19.Rxe4  , the material will be about equal @@StartBracket@@+0.5@@EndBracket@@. }
