[Black "Italian Game (1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Italian Game } 3... d6
{ Opening up the diagonal for Black's light-squared Bishop. } 4. Nc3
{ Developing the second Knight. } 4... Bg4
{ Attacking the Knight on  f3  while pinning it to the Queen. } 5. h3
{ Chasing away the Bishop.   5.Nxe5  is just bad in view of  5...Nxe5  (-3.5)  . White was hoping for  5...Bxd1??  6.Bxf7+  Ke7  7.Nd5#  . }
5... Bh5
{ By far the most played move. Over 7,000 games has this exact position. Only in 30% of those games, White was able to find the correct reply. }
6. Nxe5
{ Sacrificing the Knight while opening up the Queen's diagonal, a very good move! White has two major threats: Capturing the Bishop on  h5  and threatening a capture on  f7  . Black will decide which path White will chose. }
6... Bxd1
{ Hundreds of players were happy to capture the Queen, allowing a brilliant checkmating attack. }
7. Bxf7+ Ke7 8. Nd5#
{ Checkmate with three minor pieces! This opening trap is called 'Legal's mate', named after the French chess player François Antoine de Kermur Sire de Legal @@StartBracket@@1702–1792@@EndBracket@@. }
