[White "4. Italian Game, Other Variations"]
[Black "Schilling-Kostic Gambit (1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Italian Game } 3... Nd4
{ Schilling-Kostic Gambit, Leaving the pawn on  e5  unprotected on purpose. This poor move has been played for almost 200,000 times! This may be because if you're new to this move, there's a good chance you'll fall into a nasty trap, as we will discuss in the next variation. }
4. Nxd4
{ Exchanging Knights is best for White.   4.Nxe5  is a big mistake. We will see why in the next variation.   And  4.Ng5  is perhaps one of the most bizarre blunders in the lichess database that has been played over 1,  000  times. It obviously fails to  4...Qxg5  @@StartBracket@@-6.0@@EndBracket@@. }
4... exd4
{ 4...Qg5??  is just bad in view of  5.Nf3  Qxg2  6.Rg1  @@StartBracket@@+9.0@@EndBracket@@. }
5. O-O { Other moves are possible, like e.g.  5.d3  . } 5... Bc5
{ Thousands of players defended the pawn on  d4  with the Bishop, for no apparent reason. }
6. Bxf7+ { A temporary Bishop sacrifice, luring the King to  f7  ! } 6... Kxf7
7. Qh5+
{ Check, forking King and Bishop on  c5  . White will capture the Bishop next move. White won a pawn, doubled one of Black's pawns and took away Black's castling rights @@StartBracket@@+5.0@@EndBracket@@.  The same tactic will also work with 5. d3 instead of 5. O-O. }
*

