[White "4. Italian Game, Other Variations"]
[Black "Hungarian Defense (1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Italian Game } 3... Be7 { Hungarian Defense } 4.
d4 { Challenging Black's center. } 4... d6
{ Defending the pawn on  e5  .   We will take a look at  4...exd4  variations via the Scotch Game, Scotch Gambit, Benima Defense:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  exd4  4.Bc4  Be7  . }
5. dxe5 { Trading a pair of center pawns. } 5... Nxe5
{ A very poor move. Black should have captured with the pawn instead.  Another common move-order to get to this position is:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bc4  Be7  4.d4  , with  4...Nd7  5.dxe5  Nxe5  or  4...Nc6  5.dxe5  Nxe5  . }
6. Nxe5
{ Removing one of the defenders of  f7  , while attacking on  f7  and opening up the  d1  -  h5  diagonal for the Queen. }
6... dxe5 7. Qh5 { Threatening to capture on  f7  or  e5  . } 7... g6
{ Defending  f7  , attacking the Queen. } 8. Qxe5
{ Grabbing an important center pawn, attacking the Rook. } 8... Nf6
{ Defending the Rook while developing a Knight. Black hopes to castle next move. }
9. Bh6 { Preventing Black from castling @@StartBracket@@+3.0@@EndBracket@@! }
9... Qd6 { Offering a Queen trade. } 10. Qxd6 { Exchanging Queens. } 10... Bxd6
{ Capturing the Queen with the wrong piece... That Bishop was needed to defend the Knight on  f6  ! }
11. Bg7 { Forking Rook and Knight @@StartBracket@@+6.0@@EndBracket@@. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
