[White "4. Italian Game, Other Variations"]
[Black "Anti-Fried Liver Defense (1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Italian Game } 3... h6
{ Anti-Fried Liver Defense, A passive and dubious move played over 500,000 times, especially on lower levels!   Black didn't want to play  3...Nf6  because he is afraid of  4.Ng5  , with an attack on  f7  . With  h6  , Black prevents  Ng5  after playing  Nf6  . }
4. O-O
{ 4.O-O  is a decent alternative of  4.d4  , with the idea to bring the Rook quickly into the game. }
4... Nf6 { Attacking the pawn on  e4  . } 5. d4 { Challenging Black's center. }
5... Bd6 { Defending the pawn on  e5  with the Bishop, a poor move. } 6. dxe5
{ Trading a pair of pawns, forking two minor pieces. } 6... Nxe5
{ Most Black players capture with the Knight.  Instead, it would have been a lot better to capture with the Bishop @@StartBracket@@+1.5@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Nxe5 { Trading Knights. } 7... Bxe5 8. f4
{ Attacking the Bishop with a pawn. } 8... Bd6
{ The only safe square for the Bishop... } 9. e5
{ Forking Bishop and Knight again. } 9... Bc5+
{ Thanks to a check, Black manages to save both minor pieces. } 10. Kh1 Nh7 11.
Bxf7+
{ I prefer to keep it simple, with this temporary piece sacrifice  (+4.0)  .   Stockfish 13 however likes  11.Qg4  a lot @@StartBracket@@+5.0@@EndBracket@@. }
11... Kxf7 12. Qd5+ { Check, forking King and Bishop on  c5  . } 12... Ke8 13.
Qxc5
{ White won a pawn and Black's King will have a hard time to hide somewhere @@StartBracket@@+4.5@@EndBracket@@. }
