1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { Scotch Game } 3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ Scotch Gambit, Sacrificing a center pawn in exchange for rapid development. }
4... Qf6 { Bringing the Queen out that early isn't the best idea... } 5. c3
{ Challenging Black's center pawn. } 5... dxc3 6. Nxc3 Bb4
{ Attacking the Knight and pinning it to the King. } 7. O-O
{ Unpinning the Knight by castling. } 7... Bxc3
{ Trading a pair of minor pieces. } 8. bxc3 Qxc3
{ Grabbing a poisoned pawn, a poor move... } 9. Qd5
{ Threatening to capture the pawn on  f7  and deliver checkmate the next move. Black has no time to capture the Rook on  a1  . }
9... Qf6
{ The most popular move, but not a good one: Defending  f7  with the Queen.   The counter-intuitive  9...Nd8  is Black's best move. White should now continue with  10.Bd2  Qf6  11.Bg5  @@StartBracket@@+1.5@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Bb2
{ Attacking Black's Queen. The Bishop can't be taken, or White will give checkmate in two moves again.   10.Bg5  and  10.e5  are both suboptimal because of  10...Qe6  , taking the sting out of the attack @@StartBracket@@+1.0@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Qg6
{ Another blunder...   Black could try  10...Nge7  . But after  11.Bxf6  Nxd5  12.exd5  gxf6  13.dxc6  , material is equal, but White should have the better chance of winning the game @@StartBracket@@+3.5@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Nh4
{ Attacking the Black's Queen again. The Queen is trapped, Black's position is hopeless @@StartBracket@@+7.5@@EndBracket@@! }
