{ Scotch Gambit, Sacrificing a center pawn in exchange for rapid development. }
4... Nf6
{ Dubois Réti Defense, Developing the second Knight while attacking  e4  .  Another common move-order that results in this position is via the Italian Game, Two Knights Defense:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Nf6  4.d4  exd4  . }
5. O-O Bc5
{ Max Lange Attack. This interesting position can arrive in multiple ways, e.g. via the Italian Game, Deutz Gambit:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Bc5  4.O-O  Nf6  5.d4  exd4  . }
6. e5 { Attacking the Knight on  f6  . } 6... Ng8
{ This blunder has been made by almost 4,000 players. } 7. Ng5
{ White most promising move, threatening a fork on  f7  . } 7... Nh6
{ Defending  f7  , the most common reply.   7...Nxe5  fails to  8.Re1  , pinning the Knight to the King and renewing the threat on  f7  @@StartBracket@@+4.0@@EndBracket@@. }
