1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { Scotch Game } 3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ Scotch Gambit, Sacrificing a center pawn in exchange for rapid development. }
4... Nf6
{ Dubois Réti Defense, Developing the second Knight while attacking  e4  .  Another common move-order that results in this position is via the Italian Game, Two Knights Defense:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Nf6  4.d4  exd4  . }
5. c3
{ A poor move.   White is hoping for a sharp line like  5...dxc3  6.Nxc3  Bb4  7.e5  . But Black isn't forced to capture on  c3  of course @@StartBracket@@+0.0@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nxe4
{ Grabbing another center pawn. White's pawn on  c3  is looking ugly now, hindering the development of the Knight on  b1  . }
6. Qb3
{ Trying an attack on  f7  .   Other moves like  6.O-O  or  6.cxd4  would fail to  6...d5  @@StartBracket@@-2.0@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Qf6
{ Defending  f7  . Black has a small material edge @@StartBracket@@-1.0@@EndBracket@@. }
