1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { Scotch Game } 3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ Scotch Gambit, Sacrificing a center pawn in exchange for rapid development. }
4... Nf6
{ Dubois Réti Defense, Developing the second Knight while attacking  e4  .  Another common move-order that results in this position is via the Italian Game, Two Knights Defense:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Nf6  4.d4  exd4  . }
5. e5 { Advance Variation, Chasing away the Knight on  f6  . } 5... Ng4
{ Kingside Variation, Attacking the pawn on  e5  with two Knights. } 6. Bxf7+
{ An incorrect piece sacrifice. } 6... Kxf7 7. Ng5+
{ Check, with a discovered attack on the Knight on  g4  . } 7... Kg8
{ The best square for the King, both in practice and according to the engine. }
8. Qxg4
{ Winning the piece back.   8.Qf3  is slightly better, although not many players tried it. Black now has to find  8...Bb4+  , in order to create an escape square for the King on  f8  , e.g. after  9.c3  Qe7  10.Qd5+  Kf8  . The position is quite complicated, feel free to check some lines with an engine @@StartBracket@@-1.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8... h6
{ Kicking the Knight back, a very important move. White threatened Qf3, with checkmate on  f7  and a checkmate threat after Qb3. }
9. Nf3 d6
{ Challenging White's pawn on  e5  while attacking the Queen with the Bishop on  c8  . Material is equal, but Black does have a small edge because the initiative, control over the center, and the Bishop pair @@StartBracket@@-2.0@@EndBracket@@. }
