1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { Scotch Game } 3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ Scotch Gambit, Sacrificing a center pawn in exchange for rapid development. }
4... Nf6
{ Dubois Réti Defense, Developing the second Knight while attacking  e4  .  Another common move-order that results in this position is via the Italian Game, Two Knights Defense:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Nf6  4.d4  exd4  . }
5. e5 { Advance Variation, Chasing away the Knight on  f6  . } 5... d5
{ The best move: a counter-attack! } 6. exf6
{ A very poor move, continuing with the initial plan, ignoring White's threat. }
6... dxc4 { Winning back the piece. } 7. fxg7
{ The most played move in the position, but not a good one.   7.Qe2  forks King and pawn on  c4  , but  7...Be6  should be Black's answer @@StartBracket@@-4.0@@EndBracket@@.   And  7.O-O  could be followed by  7...gxf6  or  7...Qxf6  8.Re1+  Be6  @@StartBracket@@-4.0@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Qe7+
{ A really nice zwischenzug with excellent winning chances. And the engine likes it too! }
8. Qe2 Qxe2+ { Trading Queens. } 9. Kxe2 Bxg7
{ Black is up a pawn, has better development, center control and the Bishop pair @@StartBracket@@-5.0@@EndBracket@@. }
