10... Be6 { The only way to defend  f7  ... } 11. Nxe6
{ Trading a pair of minor pieces. } 11... fxe6 12. Ba6
{ What a move!   12...bxa6  fails to  13.Qxc6+  , forking King and Rook on  a8  @@StartBracket@@+7.5@@EndBracket@@.   12...Rb8  is bad in view of  13.Bxb7  Rxb7  14.Qxc6+  , forking King and Rook @@StartBracket@@+8.5@@EndBracket@@. }
12... O-O-O
{ The only move that allows Black to unpin his King and defend the pawn on  b7  . }
13. Qxc6
{ Capturing a piece. The Queen can't be taken since the pawn on  b7  is pinned to the King by the Bishop. }
13... bxa6 14. Qxa6+
{ Equalizing material. White's pieces are more active than Black's. Black's King is exposed @@StartBracket@@+6.0@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Scotch Game, Other Variations"]
[Black "Scotch Game, Göring Gambit, Double Pawn Sacrifice (3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { Scotch Game } 3... exd4 4. c3
{ Göring Gambit, Sacrificing a pawn for rapid development. } 4... dxc3 5. Bc4
{ Double Pawn Sacrifice, Offering the pawn on  b2  as well. } 5... cxb2 6. Bxb2
{ White has two beautiful active Bishops, eyeing on Black's kingside. This position is similar to some positions in the Center Attack, Danish Gambit. }
6... Bc5
{ A blunder, played hundreds of times. The job of this Bishop was to protect the pawn on  g7  !   Instead,  6...Bb4+  is Black's best move @@StartBracket@@-0.5@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Bxg7
{ Grabbing a free pawn, attacking the Rook. Suddenly, Black has a lost position! }
7... Bb4+ { One move too late unfortunately... } 8. Nbd2
{ Blocking the check while developing the second Knight @@StartBracket@@+7.0@@EndBracket@@.   8.Nc3  is slightly worse in view of  8...Nf6  9.Qb3  Bxc3+  10.Qxc3  Nxe4  @@StartBracket@@+4.5@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Scotch Game, Other Variations"]
[Black "Scotch Game, Steinitz Variation, Modern Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { Scotch Game } 3... exd4
{ Trading a pair of center pawns. } 4. Nxd4 Qh4
{ Steinitz Variation, A rather dubious move, attacking the pawn on  e4  with the Queen. }
5. Nc3 { Developing the second Knight, defending  e4  . } 5... Bb4
{ Modern Defense, Attacking the Knight on  c3  , pinning it to the King. } 6.
Be2 { The only move to keep an advantage! } 6... Qxe4
{ Grabbing white center pawn, attacking  g2  . The Knight on  c3  can't capture the Queen since it is pinned to the King. }
7. Nb5 { An important move to remember, threatening a fork on  c7  . } 7...
Bxc3+ { The most popular move, trading a pair of minor pieces. } 8. bxc3
{ Recapturing with the pawn to keep the attack going! } 8... Qe5
{ Defending  c7  with the Queen, a blunder.   Black should have played  8...Kd8  . And after  9.O-O  , the game is about equal @@StartBracket@@+0.5@@EndBracket@@. }
9. f4 { Chasing away the Queen. The Queen can no longer protect  c7  ! } 9...
Qc5 { Counter-attacking on  c3  . } 10. Nxc7+ { Check, forking King and Rook. }
10... Kd8 11. Nxa8
{ White is up a full Rook for now. But it won't be easy to find a good shelter for his King @@StartBracket@@+3.5@@EndBracket@@! }
