1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { Scotch Game } 3... exd4
{ Trading a pair of center pawns. } 4. Nxd4 Bc5
{ Classical Variation, Attacking the Knight on  d4  with two minor pieces. } 5.
Be3 { Defending the Knight while developing a Bishop. } 5... Qf6
{ Attacking the Knight with a third piece. } 6. Nb5
{ Blumenfeld Attack, Threatening a Knight fork on  c7  . } 6... Bxe3
{ Trading a pair of Bishops, threatening checkmate on  f2  . } 7. fxe3
{ Avoiding checkmate. } 7... Qxb2
{ This second most common move is a blunder! The pawn on  b2  is poisoned, and White now should try to trap Black's Queen.   7...Qh4+  would have been better, e.g. followed by  8.g3  Qxe4  9.Nxc7+  Kd8  10.Nxa8  Qxh1  @@StartBracket@@-0.5@@EndBracket@@. }
8. N1c3
{ A calm move, trying to trap the Queen!   8...Qb4  is the only move that limits the damage @@StartBracket@@+2.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Nb4
{ A poor move, threatening a Knight fork on  c2  .   8...Kd8  avoids a Knight fork on  c7  , but after  9.Rb1  , Black's Queen is lost @@StartBracket@@+7.0@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Rb1 { Attacking the Queen and the Knight behind her. } 9... Nxc2+
{ This looks like a dangerous move, but it only prolongs the game with a few moves.   9...Qxc2  would drop the Knight instead:  10.Rxb4  @@StartBracket@@+5.0@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Kd2 { Bravely stepping forward into a discovered check! } 10... Nxe3+
{ Discovered check, attacking the Queen on  d1  . } 11. Kxe3
{ A cool reply. Black's Queen is still trapped @@StartBracket@@+10.0@@EndBracket@@! }
