[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 { Bishop's Opening } 2... Nf6
{ Berlin Defense, Attacking  e4  . } 3. d3 { Defending the pawn on  e4  . }
3... Nc6 4. Nc3 { Vienna Hybrid Variation } 4... Be7 5. f4
{ Challenging Black's pawn in the center. } 5... d6
{ Defending the pawn on  e5  , opening the diagonal for the Bishop. } 6. Nf3
{ Increasing the pressure on  e5  , getting ready to castle. } 6... Bg4
{ Attacking the Knight on  f3  , pinning it to the Queen. } 7. O-O
{ Defending the Knight once more, while putting the King into safety. } 7...
Nd4
{ Attacking the pinned Knight with yet another minor piece. A dubious move, since the pawn on  e5  now has one defender less. }
8. fxe5 { Trading a pair of pawns in the center. } 8... dxe5
{ A blunder.   8...Bxf3  would have been better, e.g. followed by  9.gxf3  dxe5  10.f4  @@StartBracket@@+1.0@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Bxf7+
{ A temporary piece sacrifice! This sacrifice also works without Nc3 and Be7 on move 4. }
9... Kxf7
{ This was played the most. But it isn't a good move at all.   9...Kf8  10.Bb3  is better for Black @@StartBracket@@+2.0@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Nxe5+ { Check, forking King and Bishop. } 10... Ke8 11. Nxg4
{ White gets the piece back and won a pawn in the process. } 11... Nxg4
{ Exchanging Knights in order to lure the Queen away from the pawn on  c2  . }
12. Qxg4 Nxc2 { Capturing a pawn, attacking the Rook in the corner. } 13. Nd5
{ A good move to remember!   13.Rb1  isn't bad, but in that case White could lose the initiative. }
13... Nxa1
{ Another blunder. This will lose the Queen after a forced sequence of moves. }
14. Qxg7 { Attacking the Rook. } 14... Rf8 15. Rxf8+ { Trading Rooks. } 15...
Bxf8 16. Nf6+
{ Checking the King with the Knight. Notice how White's Queen covers important squares on the 7th rank. }
16... Qxf6 { A forced move... } 17. Qxf6
{ White is up in material and should be winning easily @@StartBracket@@+9.0@@EndBracket@@. }
