1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { Attacking the pawn on  e5  . } 2... Nc6 { Defending  e5  . }
3. Nc3 { Three Knights Opening } 3... Nf6 { Four Knights Game } 4. d4
{ Scotch Variation, Challenging Black's center pawn. } 4... Bb4
{ Attacking the Knight on  c3  , pinning it to the King. A rather dubious move. }
5. Nxe5
{ Krause Gambit, an interesting gambit. In Christof Sielecki's 'Keep it simple: 1.e4', dozens of wild lines are dedicated to this particular variation. }
5... Nxe5 { Exchanging a pair of Knights, simplifying the position. } 6. dxe5
{ Attacking the Knight on  f6  . } 6... Nxe4
{ Attacking the pinned Knight on  c3  with two minor pieces. } 7. Qg4
{ Activating the Queen, creating multiple threats. This is by far the best move, with excellent winning chances in practice. }
7... Nxc3
{ One of Black's typical replies, hoping for a discovered attack with the Bishop next move. }
8. Qxb4
{ 8.bxc3  is a mistake obviously, in view of  8...Bxc3  , forking King and Rook @@StartBracket@@-4.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Nd5 { The only safe square for the Knight. } 9. Qg4
{ Once again threatening to take the pawn on  g7  . White has the Bishop pair and controls the center @@StartBracket@@+3.0@@EndBracket@@. }
